In this article, President Barack Obama proclaims June 2012 as Lesbian, Gay, Bisexual, and Transgender (LGBT) Pride Month in the United States. He acknowledges the contributions of the LGBT community in the fight for equality and celebrates the progress that has been made. The Obama administration has taken various actions to advance LGBT rights, such as passing the Matthew Shepard and James Byrd, Jr., Hate Crimes Prevention Act and ending housing discrimination based on sexual orientation and gender identity. They have also expanded hospital visitation rights and ensured that insurance companies cannot deny coverage based on sexual orientation or gender identity. The president emphasizes that there is still work to be done to achieve full equality for all Americans, regardless of sexual orientation or gender identity. He calls upon the people of the United States to eliminate prejudice and celebrate the diversity of the American people.